<TEXT>
the agriculture department says farmers saw 
prices rise again in december and are winding up 1989 as a year of 
recordhigh prices eclipsing the old 12month record set five 
years ago 
prices farmers got for raw products rose 07 percent from 
november to december leaving the monthly average 21 percent above 
the level of december 1988 
higher prices for hogs cattle milk and eggs were mostly 
responsible for the increase from the november average the 
departments agricultural statistics board said friday in its final 
report of the year lower prices were reported for lettuce 
oranges cotton and broilers 
most of the price information was collected at midmonth before 
the latest freeze that swept into florida and texas destroying 
citrus and vegetable crops the preliminary figures will be revised 
next month 
the report said the december milk price was the highest on 
record and that the average for hogs was the highest since october 
1987 
john buche of the departments national agricultural statistics 
service said the preliminary 12month price average for all farm 
commodities about 147 percent of a 1977 base used for comparison 
is the highest on record 
the previous high index reading was 142 percent in 1984 he 
said the 1988 average was 138 percent 
no new figures were provided on prices farmers pay to meet 
expenses due to budget restrictions those are computed every 
three months in october the prices paid index averaged 29 
percent more than a year earlier 
on dec 20 the departments economic research service issued 
income estimates showing that net cash income of farmers in 1989 
may be in the range of 52 billion to 57 billion compared with a 
revised estimate of 572 billion in 1988 
department economists say the decline is due mostly to larger 
expenses as they put more land back into crops and to reduced 
federal payments 
net cash income is the money nationally that farmers have left 
from gross cash income during a calendar year after deducting cash 
expenses it includes government payments and proceeds from crops 
grown previously but sold during the year 
department projections for 1990 show net cash income likely 
will exceed 50 billion for the fourth consecutive year 
consumer food prices are estimated by usda economists to have 
risen about 57 percent this year the sharpest rise since 1981 
they project food prices may rise 3 percent to 5 percent in 1990 
based on the preliminary figures the december price index for 
livestock and poultry rose 24 percent from november and averaged 
97 percent more than a year ago 
the meat animal portion of the index was up 29 percent from 
november and 84 percent from december 1988 dairy prices rose 25 
percent from november and 18 percent from a year ago 
department economists predict milk output will increase in 1990 
and that the record price levels will recede 
earlier friday the department announced a 50cent reduction in 
the federal price support of milk beginning jan 1 to 1010 per 
100 pounds the cut was ordered to help stem an expected rise in 
surplus production in 1990 
under the dairy price support program usda buys surplus butter 
cheese and nonfat dry milk to bolster the price of milk at the 
farm with a lower support for 1990 officials say less surplus 
production will be bought 
crop prices overall declined 16 percent from november and 81 
percent from december 1988 including lower prices for fruit 
commercial vegetables and cotton food grains wheat and rice 
were up 27 percent from november but averaged 19 percent below a 
year ago 
