<TEXT>
parliament has repealed a constitutional 
amendment that allowed the government to suspend basic human rights 
in punjab state where sikh extremists have killed more than 7500 
people in the past seven years 
the decision taken late friday night in the final hours of the 
first parliament session convened under prime minister vp singh 
was largely a goodwill gesture 
the amendment passed in march 1988 when rajiv gandhi was prime 
minister would have expired march 30 1990 many of the measures 
imposed under it had already been lifted earlier by the gandhi 
government in hopes of easing the punjab situation 
singh has promised to seek a political solution to the punjab 
problem and has already traveled to the rich northern farming state 
in hope of opening new talks with sikh militants 
sikh extremists advocating creation of an independent nation 
for their faith in punjab have killed at least 1806 people in the 
state this year including 25 since singh took office dec 2 
the victims include hindus the countrys largest religious 
group as well as fellow sikhs considered traitors or 
nonsupportive of the militant movement 
parliaments lower house voted 3601 to repeal the 59th 
amendment to the constitution and the upper house cast a unanimous 
140 votes in favor of repeal the repeal will become effective as 
soon as it is accepted by president ramaswamy venkataraman whose 
post is primarily ceremonial 
gandhi who is now the opposition leader in parliament said 
earlier his congress party would not oppose repeal 
the policymaking lower house of which singh and gandhi are 
members had 525 seats at stake in the november election singhs 
national front and its allies have 277 seats while the congress 
party has 193 
the 59th amendment had allowed the government to declare a state 
of emergency in parts or all of punjab thereby enabling the 
government to invoke other antiterrorism laws that permit arrest 
without charge and indefinite detention these laws remain on the 
books 
singh who is a hindu like all of his predecessors as prime 
minister led his national front coalition through the november 
election with pledges to seek a political solution to punjab 
sikhs who have a slight majority in punjab have complained of 
discrimination against their faith and culture by hindus 
nationally sikhs comprise only 2 percent of indias 880 million 
people while hindus account more about 80 percent 
the sikh faith has roots in both hinduism and islam 
